practiced identifying phishing indicators in a suspicious email

## scenerio
- sender posed as microsoft and told the user to rest thier password urgently

## verdict
- I assessed the email as suspicious. This appeared to be a phising email.

## Phishing indicator
- the sender mispelt "micros0ft": replacing the letter o with a zero
- the email created urgency by saying the password would expire today
- the greeting was generic and did not addess the user by name
- the link used HTTP, which is less secure than HTTPS
- the reset link used an unusual domain

## check needed
- review the eemail header
- check whether other user recieved the same email
- analyse the URL carefully
- check whether anyone clicked the link 

## recommended actions
- not clicking the link 
- report and quarantine the email
- block the sender or domain if confirmed malicious
- reset the password only through the official microsoft website

## lesson learnt 
- phishing emails often use urgency
- fake domains
- generic greeting (user should be addressed by name)
- suspicious links to trick users 

